b": 0.5131228566169739, "span": {"begin": 1681, "end": 1694}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6770"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Steroidogenic acute regulatory protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9987987875938416, "span": {"begin": 1681, "end": 1719}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6770"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "StAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9804251194000244, "span": {"begin": 1721, "end": 1725}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2516"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "steroidogenic factor 1 binding sites", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9979320764541626, "span": {"begin": 1745, "end": 1781}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013256"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "steroid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994599223136902, "span": {"begin": 1890, "end": 1897}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "steroidogenic cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.8967910408973694, "span": {"begin": 1963, "end": 1982}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002784"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cholesterol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9985107779502869, "span": {"begin": 2010, "end": 2021}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "granulosa cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8948602080345154, "span": {"begin": 2090, "end": 2105}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002784"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cholesterol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995551705360413, "span": {"begin": 2112, "end": 2123}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011374"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9977471232414246, "span": {"begin": 2151, "end": 2163}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002784"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cholesterol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995207786560059, "span": {"begin": 2190, "end": 2201}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6770", "2984"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Steroidogenic Acute Regulatory (StAR) protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8697710037231445, "span": {"begin": 2245, "end": 2290}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6770", "2984"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "StAR protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9929722547531128, "span": {"begin": 2306, "end": 2318}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "preovulatory cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8524983525276184, "span": {"begin": 2322, "end": 2340}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6770", "2984"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "StAR protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9944199323654175, "span": {"begin": 2405, "end": 2417}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "luteinizing hormone", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9968821406364441, "span": {"begin": 2477, "end": 2496}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9986063838005066, "span": {"begin": 2498, "end": 2500}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011374"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9985479712486267, "span": {"begin": 2586, "end": 2598}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9871599674224854, "span": {"begin": 2640, "end": 2645}}], "text": "Biological state: Steroidogenic acute regulatory protein (StAR) plays important role in luteal steroidogenesis(Christenson and Devoto, 2003). Steroidogenic acute regulatory protein (StAR) controls the transport of cholesterol from the outer to inner mitochondrial membrane(Stocco, 2000). There are several pathways involved for the transport of cholesterol from different subcellular pools into the inner mitochondria(Martin et al., 2016).  Biological compartments: Cholesterol is one type of lipid which is crystalline solid with yellow colour. &nbsp;It is biosynthesized&nbsp;by animal&nbsp;cells&nbsp;and is an essential structural component of&nbsp;animal&nbsp;cell membranes (Hanukoglu, 1992). It is the precursor molecule for the synthesis all&nbsp;steroid hormones(Payne and Hales, 2004). &nbsp;Cytochrome P450 enzymes are present in most tissues of the body, and play important roles in&nbsp;hormone&nbsp;synthesis in mitochondria using cholesterol&nbsp;as precursor(Poderoso et al., 2013).  General role in biology: &nbsp;It is been reported that high &nbsp;in cholesterol levels in mitochondrial resulted several diseases like cancer, neurodegenerative diseases, steatohepatitis ischemia, and influence disease (Martin et al., 2016). The alteration in mitochondrial cholesterol import may change the cholesterol concentrations that may lead to proper mitochondrial function along with biophysical properties of mitochondrial membranes. In absence of StAR protein, cholesterol transport into the mitochondria did not occurs leading to&nbsp; no conversion of progesterone from cholesterol precursors doesn&rsquo;t occur(Kiriakidou et al., 1996; Pescador et al., 1996). All Steroidogenic acute regulatory protein (StAR) promoters contain steroidogenic factor 1 binding sites which is responsible for sex hormones regulation(Manna et al., 2002).  One of the important function of the steroid hormones is maintaining reproductive capacity. For this purpose, steroidogenic cells must move large amounts of cholesterol from the outer mitochondrial membrane to the inner membrane. In the granulosa cells, this cholesterol is ultimately converted to progesterone. The initial transport of cholesterol across the mitochondrial membrane requires Steroidogenic Acute Regulatory (StAR) protein. Expression of StAR protein in preovulatory cells of the developing follicle is low. The dramatic upregulation of StAR protein expression within the dominant follicle is found after the luteinizing hormone (LH) surge. This upregulation allows the corpus luteum to produce substantial amounts of progesterone to maintain the reproductive capacity in human/animal (Men et al., 2017; Stocco, 2000).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:54:32 +0000 2026"}